body:
>I performed it on the whole image (I thought reconstructing from patches was slower than just infering on the whole image).

@jeanyves-yang : I agree with you that we can train with overlapping patches. The learned weight is for the patch size (i.e 64x64x64). But it is not clear that how can we use the learned weight to predict the deformation if the input is whole image. Because the learned weight is for patch only.

For example, the input image is 256x256x256. We train the network with cropped input size of 64x64x64 (patch-based). Then the trained model is for the cropped image, instead of whole image (256x256x256).

@adalca : Thanks for value discussion. I just want to make clear the meaning of
>since having the correct deformation at the edges of the images is hard in that case.
What do you mean the edge of the image? Is edge of bounding box that defined the patches? The reason is hard to correct deformation because it cannot expand in the edge region, right?
